\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Souls and States\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Augustine never regarded himself as a saint, undergoing a slow and painful conversion to Christianity\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Theological training was less important than firmness of will, persuasiveness in rhetoric, and the pragmatism necessary to get things done.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Augustine set out to reconcile faith with reason. The confessions began the journey with a self-imposed public humiliation, leaving all the more room for his subsequent work to soar\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Man must manage unknowns, for God has endowed him \'97 or cursed him \'97 with free will. That is the price of original sin, but it\'92s also the opportunity that allows hope: human existence  need not be pointless: man isn\'92t at the mercy of capricious gods.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \cf2 The genius of Augustine is that he concerns himself more with tensions than their sources: order versus justice, war versus peace, Caesar versus God. He creates polarities as gravitational forces without trying to say what gravity is.\cf0 \
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 He\'92s comfortable, to a point, with contradictions\'85making his teachings procedural, not absolute.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 For all the harshness in rooting out heretics, Augustine preferred persuasion on issues of war and peace\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 A larger piece is that Augustine never appeared wholeheartedly a monotheist. He worshipped Reason as much as he worshipped God, but he never showed God to be any more bound by Reason than Jupiter had been: \'93The two roles are quite incompatible.\'94 This is where Augustine was uncomfortable with contradictions.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Augustine regards military service as necessary to sustain the state with out which Christianity can\'92t survive\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Machiavelli had a first-rate intelligence \'97 holding in mind while functioning \'97 and that Augustine, for all his diligence, fell short. \
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Machiavelli found \'93lightness of being\'94 bearable. For Augustine, it was un-endurable\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 virtu \'97 planning without praying\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \cf2 \'93Lightness of Being\'94 is the ability, if not to find the good in bad things, then at least to remain afloat among them, perhaps to swim or to sail through them, possibly even to take precautions that can keep you dry. It\'92s not to locate logic in misfortunes, or to show that they\'92re for the best because they reflect God\'92s will.\cf0  That\'92s for Augustine the hedgehog, the ponderous Pangloss of his day.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \cf3 Panglossian\cf0  \'97 character in voltaire whom is unreasonably optimistic and naive\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Aspirations are not always capabilities, despite how we often try to connect them with checklists\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Machiavelli was one of the founding thinkers of utilitarianism.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Borja didn\'92t just sack his subordinates: he disassembled them and displayed the pieces. The shock and awe accomplished its purpose: at the cost of one life, others were saved that would have been lost if a new revolt had broken out. \
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \'93If you have to use force, don\'92t destroy what you are trying to preserve\'94\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \'93Justice is no more reasonable than what a person\'92s prudence tells him he must acquire for himself, or must submit to, because men cannot afford justice in any sense that transcends their own preservation.\'94\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \'93A prince can never secure himself among the people, for they are too many. He can however, secure himself among the great, because they are few.\'94\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 utilitarian morality \'97 proportioning your actions to your objective, not to progress from one nebulous city to another, but because some things have been shown to work an others haven\'92t\'94\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \'85Where Augustine is a closeted polytheist, uneasily juggling the incompatibility of God and Reason\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \cf2 You proportion aspirations to capabilities. These are opposites \'97 the first being free from limits and the second being bound by them \'97 but they must connect. That happens only when you hold both in mind simultaneously.\cf0 \
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Augustine\'92s City of God no longer exists on earth. The City of Man, which survives, has no single path to salvation. The belief that the correct, objectively valid solution to the question of how men should live can in principle be discovered, is itself in principle not true.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 The roots of toleration: \'93historically the product of the realization of the irreconcilability of equally dogmatic faiths, and the practical improbability of complete victory of one over the other.\
