\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Princes as Pivots\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Phillip II rushes from crisis to crisis, rarely resting, never fully in control. He\'92s whacking moles, and they pop up everywhere. Elizabeth, in contrast, refuses to hurry. She\'92ll whack when she has to, but she resists unnecessary expenditures of resources, energy, reputation, and \'97 unusual for a monarch \'97 virginity.\
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Phillip II was unable to see past the responsibilities that engulfed him and, as a consequence, the paperwork swamped him. While Elizabeth freely delegated so that she had time to strategize and remain clear of mind.\
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Phillip II failed to see incompatibles, and hence the need to pursue certain objectives at the expense of others. The king resisted prioritizing ends, even though God himself had chosen to selectively provide means\
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Elizabeth\'92s lightness allowed flirtation, which costs less than obligation, whether to suiters or the their realms\
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \cf2 Pivoting requires gyroscopes. Elizabeth balanced purposefulness with imagination, guile, humor, timing, and an economy in movement that, however extravagant her display, kept her steady on the tightrope she walked. She, without visible effort, retained the initiative in all she did. She never felt not up to her role.\cf0 \
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Machiavelli, thinking gyroscopically, advised his prince to be a lion and a fox, the former to frighten wolves, the latter to detect snares. Elizabeth went him one better, by being a lion, a fox and female. \
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 For Phillip II, micromanaging an empire on which the sun never set tended to blur his vision\
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \cf3 hendiadys\cf0  \'97 \
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl2
\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 a complex idea expressed by two words connected by a copulative conjunction \'85 how two things become one\
\ls5\ilvl2
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 the expression of a single idea by two words connected with \'93and,\'94 e.g., nice and warm, when one could be used to modify the other, as in nicely warm.\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 The church, more than anyone suspects, masters contradictions and therefore links the cities of God and Man. Counterfactuals, like ghosts, should haunt historians.\
