\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 New Worlds\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \cf2 Assuming stability is one of the ways ruins get made, resilience accommodates the unexpected\
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 The absence of close control by the British crown in the early stages of colonization left considerable latitude for the evolution of those forms of government that seemed most appropriate  to the people actively involved in the process of overseas enterprise and settlement\
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 \cf4 Controlled environments encourage complacency, making it hard to cope when controls break down as they sooner or later must. Constant disruptions, however, prevent recuperation,  nothing is ever healthy. There is a balance then, between integrative and disintegrative processes in the natural world \'97 and edge of chaos, so to speak \'97 where adaptation, especially self-organization, tends to occur. New political worlds work similarly.\cf0 \
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Elizabeth would have found her successor\'92s efforts to reconcile opposites dangerously foolish. She understood political horticulture: that things grow best when variety is allowed and roots aren\'92t too closely examined.\
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Jefferson was a genius because he could conceal contradictions in abstractions\
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Governments should balance dissatisfactions, set precedents rather than be bound by them and prefer proportionality to consistency\
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 The American experiment was \'93whether societies of men are really capable or not of establishing good government from reflection and choice, or whether they are forever destined to depend for their political constitutions on accident and force.\
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 No strategy anticipates all contingencies, that every solution creates new problems, and that these can, at times, overwhelm. \
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Knowing the need to proportion aspirations to capabilities, recognizing the incompatibilities in good things, they chose to save their new state, and leave it to their descendants the saving of its soul. (US and slavery)\
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 By balancing internal interests, external expansion can occur\
\ls6\ilvl1
\f2\fs20 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 Bolivar argued that New Spain had political immaturity because Spain had so tightly controlled its territories as to keep them in a \'93permanent infancy\'94 unable to command self-respect.\
